    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n<meta charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n<meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\" />\n<title>Dynamic Programming Demo</title>\n<style>\n  body {\n    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n    margin: 2rem;\n    background: #fafafa;\n    color: #222;\n    max-width: 700px;\n  }\n  h1 {\n    color: #0275d8;\n  }\n  section {\n    margin-bottom: 2rem;\n    background: #fff;\n    padding: 1rem 1.5rem;\n    border-radius: 6px;\n    box-shadow: 0 3px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);\n  }\n  label {\n    display: block;\n    margin: 0.5rem 0 0.3rem;\n  }\n  input[type=\"number\"] {\n    width: 80px;\n    font-size: 1rem;\n    padding: 0.3rem;\n    margin-right: 0.5rem;\n  }\n  button {\n    background-color: #0275d8;\n    color: white;\n    font-weight: bold;\n    border: none;\n    padding: 0.5rem 1rem;\n    border-radius: 4px;\n    cursor: pointer;\n    transition: background-color 0.2s ease;\n  }\n  button:hover {\n    background-color: #025aa5;\n  }\n  pre {\n    background: #f0f0f0;\n    padding: 1rem;\n    border-radius: 4px;\n    overflow-x: auto;\n  }\n  .output {\n    margin-top: 1rem;\n    background: #eef8ff;\n    padding: 1rem;\n    border-left: 4px solid #0275d8;\n    white-space: pre-wrap;\n  }\n  small {\n    color: #666;\n  }\n</style>\n</head>\n<body>\n<h1>Dynamic Programming Demo: Fibonacci Numbers</h1>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Dynamic Programming (DP) is an optimization technique used to solve problems\n    by breaking them down into simpler subproblems and storing the results\n    to avoid redundant computations.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Here, we'll compute Fibonacci numbers using three different approaches to see\n    how dynamic programming improves efficiency:\n  </p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Naive recursion</strong> - exponential time (slow)</li>\n    <li><strong>Memoization (Top-down DP)</strong> - cache results of recursion</li>\n    <li><strong>Tabulation (Bottom-up DP)</strong> - iterative and fills a table</li>\n  </ul>\n</section>\n\n<section>\n  <label for=\"fibInput\">Enter n (Fib index):</label>\n  <input type=\"number\" id=\"fibInput\" min=\"0\" max=\"50\" value=\"30\" />\n  <button id=\"calcBtn\">Calculate</button>\n  <div class=\"output\" id=\"output\">\n    Result and performance will appear here.\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<section>\n  <h2>Explanation</h2>\n  <p>\n    The Fibonacci sequence is defined as:\n  </p>\n  <pre>\nFib(0) = 0\nFib(1) = 1\nFib(n) = Fib(n-1) + Fib(n-2) for n ≥ 2\n  </pre>\n  <p>\n    The naive recursive method computes many values repeatedly, causing exponential runtime. \n    Memoization stores intermediate subproblem results to avoid recomputation, and tabulation builds the solution bottom-up iteratively.\n  </p>\n</section>\n\n<script>\n  // Naive recursive approach\n  function fibNaive(n) {\n    if (n <= 1) return n;\n    return fibNaive(n - 1) + fibNaive(n - 2);\n  }\n\n  // Memoization (Top-down DP)\n  function fibMemo(n, memo = {}) {\n    if (n <= 1) return n;\n    if (memo[n] !== undefined) return memo[n];\n    memo[n] = fibMemo(n - 1, memo) + fibMemo(n - 2, memo);\n    return memo[n];\n  }\n\n  // Tabulation (Bottom-up DP)\n  function fibTab(n) {\n    if (n <= 1) return n;\n    const dp = new Array(n + 1);\n    dp[0] = 0;\n    dp[1] = 1;\n    for (let i = 2; i <= n; i++) {\n      dp[i] = dp[i - 1] + dp[i - 2];\n    }\n    return dp[n];\n  }\n\n  // Utility to measure runtime in milliseconds\n  function measure(fn, arg) {\n    const start = performance.now();\n    const result = fn(arg);\n    const end = performance.now();\n    return { result, time: (end - start).toFixed(3) };\n  }\n\n  const outputElem = document.getElementById(\"output\");\n  const fibInput = document.getElementById(\"fibInput\");\n  const calcBtn = document.getElementById(\"calcBtn\");\n\n  calcBtn.addEventListener(\"click\", () => {\n    const nRaw = fibInput.value;\n    const n = Number(nRaw);\n    // Validate input\n    if (isNaN(n) || n < 0 || n > 50 || !Number.isInteger(n)) {\n      outputElem.textContent = \"Please enter an integer n between 0 and 50.\";\n      return;\n    }\n\n    outputElem.textContent = \"Calculating...\";\n\n    setTimeout(() => {\n      // For large n, naive will be very slow, so limit attempts for naive\n      let naiveResult = \"...skipped for performance (n>35)\";\n      let naiveTime = \"\";\n\n      if (n <= 35) {\n        // Naive recursion can get very slow beyond ~35\n        const naive = measure(fibNaive, n);\n        naiveResult = naive.result;\n        naiveTime = naive.time;\n      }\n\n      // Memoized recursion\n      const memo = measure(fibMemo, n);\n\n      // Tabulated iterative\n      const tab = measure(fibTab, n);\n\n      let resText = \n`Fib(${n}) results:\n\nNaive recursion:           ${naiveResult} ${naiveTime ? `(Time: ${naiveTime} ms)` : \"\"}\nMemoization (Top-down DP): ${memo.result} (Time: ${memo.time} ms)\nTabulation (Bottom-up DP): ${tab.result} (Time: ${tab.time} ms)\n\nNote:\n- Naive recursion time grows exponentially and is skipped for n > 35.\n- Memoization and tabulation run efficiently even for n=50.\n`;\n\n      outputElem.textContent = resText;\n    }, 50);\n  });\n\n// Prefill example result on load\nwindow.addEventListener(\"load\", () => calcBtn.click());\n\n</script>\n</body>\n</html>"
  },
